As Mary wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/20/2004 at 12:22:24 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Let g(x)= /cosx-1/.  THe maximum value attained by g on the closed 
>interval [0,2pi) is for x equal to ???
>
>[Difficulty]
>I am not sure whether to actually graph the problem.  If so, what is 
>a "closed interval [0, 2pi]"?  How do I mark off the graph and graph 
>the equation?  And how do I then find the max value?
>
>[Thoughts]
>I think the [0, 2pi] should go on both the x and y axis, but I don't 
>know what goes in between or how to graph the equation.  Please Help!

Hello Mary,

On the closed interval [0,2pi] means that 0 <= x <= 2pi, that is, x varies over the interval 
from 0 to 2pi, including the endpoints.

Because cos(pi)=-1, g(-1)=2 and this is the maximum value.


